/proc is a virtual filesystem in Linux that exposes kernel and process information to user space.
It doesn’t exist on disk — it’s generated dynamically by the kernel.
What <linux/proc_fs.h> Provides

This header gives you functions and structures to:

Create entries in /proc

Remove entries

Define read/write handlers

Work with struct proc_dir_entry
🧠 What /proc Is Used For

Process information (/proc/<pid>/)

Kernel parameters (/proc/sys/)

System statistics (cpuinfo, meminfo)

Legacy driver interfaces

Quick debugging interfaces
| Feature                      | `/proc`              |
| ---------------------------- | -------------------- |
| Originally for               | Process info         |
| Structure style              | Less strict          |
| Data format                  | Often free-form text |
| Stable ABI?                  | ❌ No guarantee       |
| Recommended for new drivers? | ❌ Usually no         |

sysfs Filesystem
Designed to expose kernel objects (kobjects) and device model information.
What sysfs Is Used For

Devices

Drivers

Kernel subsystems

Hardware attributes

Runtime configuration
| Feature                      | `sysfs`                        |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| Designed for                 | Device model                   |
| Structure style              | Strict hierarchy               |
| Data format                  | One value per file             |
| Stable ABI?                  | ✅ Yes (userspace relies on it) |
| Recommended for new drivers? | ✅ Yes                          |

| Category             | `/proc`                    | `sysfs`                  |
| -------------------- | -------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| Main goal            | Process + misc kernel info | Device model exposure    |
| Formatting           | Flexible text blobs        | Strict: 1 value per file |
| Backed by            | proc_fs                    | kobjects                 |
| Stability            | Not guaranteed             | Must remain stable       |
| Modern driver config | ❌ Avoid                    | ✅ Use this               |

When To Use Which?
✅ Use sysfs if:

Writing a new device driver

Exposing device attributes

Configuring hardware

You need a stable userspace ABI

⚠️ Use /proc if:

Debugging

Kernel statistics

Legacy support

Quick testing
What is the seq_file Interface?
🔹 What is seq_file?

It is a kernel helper interface used to safely generate large sequential output.

It handles:

Buffering

Partial reads

Position tracking

Multiple reads

Pagination

| Feature        | PROCFS             | seq_file                  |
| -------------- | ------------------ | ------------------------- |
| What it is     | Virtual filesystem | Output helper API         |
| Where it lives | `/proc`            | Inside kernel code        |
| Purpose        | Expose kernel info | Safely print large output |
| Used together? | Yes                | Yes                       |
User runs: cat /proc/proc_inspect
           ↓
Kernel sees file read
           ↓
proc_open() called
           ↓
seq_file allocates buffer
           ↓
proc_show() fills data using seq_printf()
           ↓
User sees output

